"The war in Ukraine will be one of the most digital conflicts we’ve ever seen. With a little caution, we can ensure we’re not unwitting combatants"

Read more
🔵Do a little digging and consider the source – did the content originate from a partisan actor, an expert, a citizen on the ground? Does it seem authentic or too good to be true?

So what can we do?

🔵Follow reputable sources, especially media organisations with reporters on the ground in Ukraine
🔵Look for confirmation from the open source community that the footage you’re looking at has actually occurred before sharing it
Sharing unconfirmed videos and photos can inflame tensions and endanger lives. It can unwittingly support the false narratives that Russia has tried to spin

Russia has been known to share video game footage in place of real satellite images, as well as misattribute photos and videos to claim atrocities that have not occurred. 

"We expect to see more fakes and manipulation as the war progresses," says @wiczipedia

At the @Cen4infoRes, an independent UK social enterprise that identifies, counters and exposes disinformation, they have already seen footage from the civil war in Syria attributed to today’s violence in Ukraine

Just as social media is part of modern life, disinformation is part of modern conflict – and it’s up to each of us to make sure we aren’t unwittingly playing a hand in amplifying it, writes @wiczipedia

Women think about saying those three words after 138.9 days, around four and a half months

A study from 2010 found that men fall in love more easily than women and a separate 2011 study found that men start to think about saying “I love you” after 97.3 days on average — a little over three months
“For some people this [falling in love in 10 days] is totally possible,” Roberts says

While we may scoff at the thought of seeing people “fall in love” in less than two weeks, a YouGov poll from 2017 found that 16 percent  of Britons have told a new romantic partner that they love them within the first month of dating, and 3 percent  have said it within the first week

While Roberts says that love can develop from an intense physical attraction, for the contestants of Love Is Blind, it’s more likely to be a deep friendship that develops initially and the fact they have been “thrown together in exceptional circumstances”
“When we feel like someone understands us, hears us and sees us and accepts us for our true authentic selves, then love is likely to blossom”
Holly Roberts, a counsellor at @Relate_charity, says it’s all about connection. “The spark you feel when you meet that certain special person is so hard to define, but you just know it’s there”

Two couples from the original series are still happily married two years on since the first season aired. 

So is it really possible to fall in love in just 10 days?
During these 10 days, some people form connections so strong that they decide to get engaged, still sight unseen 💍
The premise of Love Is Blind is simple: 30 single men and women spend 10 days in “pods” getting to know the members of the opposite sex, without ever seeing their faces
As season two of Netflix’s reality series comes to an end, we asked relationship experts whether it’s really possible to fall in love with a stranger in less than two weeks

The two pipelines together would have allowed Russia to send gas west by means other than directly through its neighbour’s territory, which it previously relied upon
Nord Stream 2 would have enabled Russia to pump an estimated additional 55 billion cubic metres of gas to Germany each year, doubling its present capacity and increasing its regional energy dominance
That may now never happen, after the German chancellor's announcement that the pipeline would be blocked in retaliation for Russian aggression on its border with Ukraine

Construction on the project was completed in September 2021 at a cost of £8.3bn but it has yet to receive the necessary European regulatory approval to permit its operator, Russian state-owned gas giant Gazprom, to turn on the taps
The pipeline is intended for the delivery of natural gas to central Europe via the Baltic Sea

What is the Nord Stream 2 pipeline?

It is a 745-mile pipeline stretching between Ust-Luga near western Russia’s border with Estonia and Greifswald in northeastern Germany.

Germany has halted approval of the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline from Russia after Vladimir Putin formally recognised the independence of two breakaway regions in eastern Ukraine

“All the big loves of my life have been a f***ing rollercoaster. Tears, laughter, craziness. I’d love one that isn’t. I’d love a nice wave.”

Read the full story

Haim says, like Gary and Alana in the film, she understands the impulse to keep going back to someone you love, just to see if this time the outcome might be different

“Everyone wants a relationship that feels like cinema,” she says.

“But it was nice to go into something where you had no control. Like it was already done. I’m so used to having to think about all of it – writing, recording, touring, lighting – that it was nice to not do anything but act”
“Me and my sisters actually like the term ‘control freak’, because that’s what we are when it comes to our music. We’ve always been that way”
“I also went through that stage where you don’t think you’re an adult but you’re considered an adult, and you have no idea what the f*** you’re doing with your life”
Haim dazzles with her performance capturing a specific kind of early-adult growing pain. She isn’t surprised that her character’s uncertainty has struck a chord with the film’s fans
Anderson wrote Licorice Pizza – and its main character Alana Kane – for Haim, having directed Alana and her elder sisters in a number of music videos
It’s her acting debut, not that you’d know. She’s convinced it’s all her director’s doing. “If you have him on your side,” she says, “you feel like you can conquer anything”
Alana Haim – one-third of sisterly rock trio @HAIMtheband – is a Bafta and Golden Globe nominee for Paul Thomas Anderson’s balmy romance Licorice Pizza

Growing up, Grohl was obsessed with the macabre and 'knew everything about the Manson Family.'

“My friend called me and said, ‘Guess where we’re swimming today? The house where Sharon Tate was killed by the Manson Family’”
“Sometimes we’ll hang out at a friend’s house and just dance until four o’clock in the morning, and we’ll play ‘Chaise Longue’ on repeat, like over and over and over and over and over again”

As well as his long-standing and well-documented respect for @billieeilish, Grohl is currently obsessed with Isle of Wight duo Wet Leg.

“Wet Leg are about to take over America,” he grins.

“There’s a lot of great young bands that are f***ing killing it and have devoted fan bases. They might not be as popular as Nicki Minaj, but honestly, when I see f***ing Billie Eilish, that’s rock’n’roll to me. She started a revolution and took over the world”

Is rock’n’roll still relevant?

“Well, I think you have to define ‘relevant’,” he starts. “It’s hard for us to say that rock’n’roll is in a rough patch, because we get up on stage and there’ll be thousands of people f***ing going bananas and singing along to our songs”

🎸 2022 -

The forthcoming festival has invited the biggest names in music to reawaken it from its three-year interruption.

Harry Styles is making his desert debut, joined by Billie Eilish and Kanye West.

🎶 2018 -

“Beychella” was coined after the iconic Beyoncé made history as the first Black woman to headline the festival. 

Eminem and The Weeknd rounded out the slate for an R&B and rap-filled event.

🎸 2017 -

When Beyoncé became pregnant with twins, she pulled out of her headlining slot, leaving Lady Gaga to take her place.

Kendrick Lamar also made his debut appearance.

🎶 2010 - 

This year Jay-Z became their first-ever rap headliner.

🎸 2008 -

As a last-minute attempt to raise ticket sales, Prince was added to the playbill only weeks before the 2008 festival was scheduled to take place.

🎶 2003 -

Welcoming the Beastie Boys and Red Hot Chili Peppers to the main stage doubled down on the currency of rock music. 

That weekend jumpstarted the onsite camping ritual too.

🎸 1999 -

Coachella’s inception into the world of festivals perfectly aligned with the post-grunge era, hence, its inaugural headliners of influential rock bands, Rage Against the Machine and Tool
Throughout its 23 years, the desert festival has led with the biggest names in music. @IngaParkel runs through Coachella’s entire history of star-studded headliners since 1999

Experts say part of the problem is financial and the WFP is short of funds because country donors have not contributed enough.
Earlier this month, officials said 31,000 people in Yemen were experiencing famine and that 161,000 were expected to have reached that predicament by June.

Officials have said one of the countries where emergency supplies to families have already been cut is Yemen, where eight million people have since December been receiving half the agency’s minimum daily ration.

“Ukraine, together with Russia, is the breadbasket of the world. Ukraine by itself produces enough food every year for about 400 million people. A lot of that is exported," Martin Penner, the WFP’s deputy head of global communications, tells @Independent
Russia and Ukraine produce as much as 30 per cent of the world’s wheat, and Vladimir Putin’s invasion of his neighbour is poised to push the cost of that staple product higher on global markets
Officials at the United Nations World Food Programme (WFP) had already warned up 44 million people, spread across 38 nations, were on the edge of famine, before the conflict.

Top famine and hunger experts have warned that millions of people around the world could face catastrophe as a result of Russia’s invasion of Ukraine and the threat to one of the most crucial global breadbaskets.
